"script": "An old thermostat clicks your heater on and off all day, with no battery and no chip inside. So how does a dumb little box know the temperature? Hidden in there is a coiled strip made of two different metals bonded together. And here's the trick: one metal expands faster than the other when heated. So as the room warms, the strip curls one way, and as it cools, it curls back. Then that bend tips a tiny blob of mercury, closing a circuit. And this simple curl of metal is what fires up your furnace.",
